The standard approach in .NET is to **wrap file system calls behind an interface** and inject it:

```csharp
public interface IFileSystem
{
    string ReadAllText(string path);
    void WriteAllText(string path, string contents);
    bool DirectoryExists(string path);
}
```

Then inject `IFileSystem` into your classes. In production, the implementation delegates to `System.IO.File`/`Directory`. In tests, you mock it or use an in-memory fake.

**Alternatively**, use the existing [`System.IO.Abstractions`](https://www.nuget.org/packages/System.IO.Abstractions) NuGet package, which provides `IFileSystem` out of the box plus a `MockFileSystem` for testing—saves you from maintaining your own wrapper.

**Quick steps:**
1. `dotnet add package System.IO.Abstractions`
2. Replace `File.ReadAllText(...)` → `_fileSystem.File.ReadAllText(...)`
3. Register `FileSystem` in DI; inject `IFileSystem` where needed.
4. In tests, use `new MockFileSystem(...)` from `System.IO.Abstractions.TestingHelpers`.
